Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: Existing work in kNN-MT has primarily focused on improving retrieval through either datastore pruning (Paper 1), adaptive selection of *k* per token (Paper 2), or interpolation weighting based on retrieval quality (Paper 3). While these approaches enhance performance, they largely treat the retrieval process as a black box that operates on surface-level similarity—typically based on encoder representations of source sentences. However, this ignores rich linguistic structure present in the source input, such as syntactic dependencies, semantic roles, and morphological features, which could guide more informed and interpretable retrieval. My intuition is that not all parts of a source sentence contribute equally to translation disambiguation; for instance, rare named entities or technical terms may require precise matches, while function words may benefit from broader generalization. By explicitly modeling source-side linguistic structures—such as dependency trees, part-of-speech tags, or semantic frames—we can design an adaptive retrieval mechanism that selectively emphasizes structurally aligned examples in the datastore. This would allow the model to retrieve neighbors not just based on vector proximity, but also on structural compatibility, leading to more accurate and interpretable predictions. Unlike prior work, this idea integrates deep linguistic analysis into the retrieval decision process, enabling both performance gains and explainability: we can trace *why* certain examples were retrieved based on their structural alignment with the query. Furthermore, it opens the door to dynamic retrieval strategies where different parts of the sentence modulate retrieval sensitivity—e.g., stricter matching near low-frequency content words, looser elsewhere. This approach differs fundamentally from Papers 1–3 by introducing *structured guidance* into retrieval, rather than post-hoc adjustments or statistical corrections.

